key_findings: 1) The orbiter measured the temperatures of the atmosphere and areas of the surface of Mars
2) The orbiter used an infrared grating spetrometer to measure solar infrared radiation reflected by the surface
3) The lander picked up a handful of Martian soil, heated it up to 500 degrees Celsius and checked the dirt for signs of organics. No organics were found

4) Gas Exchange Experimentchecked for organisms in the soil by saturating them with nurtient and water vapour. This build up of gasses meant the microbes in the test sample has kick-started either matabolism to gorge themselves

5) Carbon Assimilating Experiment tested for organisms in the soil by monitoring the release of radioactive gas. A drop of nutrient solution containing carbon-14 was added to the soil sample. Any organisms would eat the nutrients and get rid of the radioactive gas

key_findings: 1) Consisted of a lander renamed Carl Sagan Memorial Station and a lightweight rover named Sojourner
2) Carried scientific instruments to analyse the Martian atmosphere, climate, geology and composition of its rocks and soil
3) The infrared camera could not detect blue light as the lens blocked wavelength below 500nm
4) The sojourner travelled approximately 100m, never more than 12m from the pathfinder station

5) Entered the Martian atmospehere and landed using an entry capsule to slow down to 370m/s before a supersonic parachute was deployed to slow down to 68m/s. At 355m above the ground the airbags were inflated, the onboard computer calculated the best time to fire the rockets to slow the velocity down to a level the airbags could cushion the fall
6) The cost of the pathfinder mission cost one fifteeth the cost of a Viking Mission
problems: Sojourner contained a bug in the parallel processing software after the rover has landed. The bug only occurrred during certain unanticipated heavy-load conditions. The problem was due to computer resets caused by priority inversion

key_findings: It was the first mission to Mars led by a public university in NASA history
search for environments suitable for microbial life on Mars, and to research the history of water there since existing data indicated its presence
"Follow the water" NASA strategy
This marks the first time ever one spacecraft has photographed another in the act of landing on a planet
Mars Scout Programme
Preliminary wet chemistry lab results showed the surface soil is moderately alkaline, between pH 8 and 9. Magnesium, sodium, potassium and chloride ions were found

the overall level of salinity is modest. Chloride levels were low, and thus the bulk of the anions present were not initially identified. The pH and salinity level were viewed as benign from the standpoint of biology

Results published in the journal Science after the mission ended 
reported that chloride, bicarbonate, magnesium, sodium potassium, 
calcium, and possibly sulfate were detected in the samples. The pH was 
narrowed down to 7.7 ±0.5. Perchlorate (ClO4), a strong oxidizer
 at elevated temperatures, was detected. This was a significant 
discovery as perchlorate has the potential of being used for rocket fuel
 and as a source of oxygen for future colonists.
"Triumph" in binary code was the last message from Phoenex (01010100 01110010 01101001 01110101 01101101 01110000 01101000)
